accessibility.text: Avulsion history
• The migration pattern of the delta lobes is not reproduced in the “no-avulsion” scenario
• However the along-strike progradation of the shelf-edge delta is completed, suggesting that the latter is mostly constrained by the base SED, fault-controlled topography.
Bonaparte shelf edge delta
Impact of higher fault throw and subsidence rates
• Higher subsidence and fault throw rates result in considerably less progradation rates at the shelf-margin and along the continental slope.
Low sediment input rates
• With a mean water and sediment discharge of 6.7 km3/year and 5.3 Mt/year respectively, this simulation is in the range of very-low supply setting.
• Cumulative sediment thickness of the SED reaches a maximum of 225 m. This is 15% lower than the cumulative thickness measured from the seismic dataset.
High sediment input rates
• With a mean water and sediment discharge of 17 km3/year and 13.6 Mt/year respectively, this simulation is in the range of systems such as the modern (post-dam) Ebro river-delta.
• High sediment flux promotes downstepping progradation geometries (forced regression) particularly along-strike.
• Cumulative sediment thickness reaches 375 m, as opposed to a maximum 355 m observed in the dataset (+5 %).
Exploring parameters space: Uncertainties quantification

Low sediment supply rates are required to reproduce a comparable cumulative sediment thickness
Initial, fault-controlled topography is key to reproduce similar along-strike and progradation in clinoform shape
Source avulsion history is the key factor controlling the overall delta architecture
